As one former ASTM panel member told me, "It sounds like a scientific thing, developing a fuel, but there‚Äôs always economic and political facets to it, and money drives it all."

Tasked with regulating aircraft, not fuels, the FAA has largely followed the industry's lead. Though it's ostensibly been working since 2012 to spur development of lead-free fuels, those efforts have failed.

Those specifications are viewed as key safety checks, and it's really hard to market a fuel without them. But the companies sitting on the subcommittee are the same ones profiting from selling leaded fuel. They've blocked specifications for unleaded alternatives over 30 years.

The answer is a little-known standard-setting organization called ASTM. Representatives from all the major oil companies and airplane manufacturers sit on their aviation fuels subcommittee, which requires unanimous votes to approve specifications for new fuels.

But there were multiple promising efforts in the 1990s to develop lead-free aviation fuels. Including one fuel from a Swedish inventor that is widely used in the Nordic nation today. Why didn't those become the norm in the US, too?

Leaded gasoline for cars was banned decades ago. At the time, it seemed too complicated to get the lead out of aviation fuel, in part because lead is key to boosting octane, which prevents engines from misfiring and being torn apart mid-flight.

Those emissions have real-world consequences. In East San Jose, Calif., toddlers living near a general aviation airport were found to have lead in their blood at levels comparable to kids' during the height of the Flint, Mich., drinking water crisis.

Lead is a neurotoxin linked to lower IQ and learning problems. There is no safe level of lead, according to the CDC. The biggest source of lead in the air today? Emissions from small aircraft, like helicopters and two-to-ten seater airplanes.
